	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Coffee price volatility raises the challenge of ensuring primary producers benefit from rising markets</h1>

			
			<h4>
												09 August 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Coffee market analysts are suggesting that with a cut in estimates for the arabica production surplus (down 900,000 bags to 5.6m bags for Arabica production in 2010–11), ‘coffee markets will in 2011-12 witness more of the supply squeezes’, with a possible increase in ‘extreme price volatility’. While prices fell back from ‘the 34-year highs above 300 cents a pound reached in April’ (to 266 c/lb for July delivery), it is argued that prices could rise back as high as 318 c/lb for arabica.</p><p>Forecasts for a robusta coffee surplus were also cut (by 290,000 bags to 4.9m bags), reflecting La Niña weather effects in Indonesia. These are supported by International Coffee Organisation estimates, which put the 2011–12 harvest at 130m bags, compared to consumption in 2010 of 134m bags.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>Agrimoney.com</i>, ‘Coffee price rally could find fresh legs, says VM’, 27 May 2011<br />

<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/news/coffee-price-rally-could-find-fresh-legs-says-vm--3193.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/news/coffee-price-rally-could-find-fresh-legs-s...</a> <br />
<i>Agrimoney.com</i>, ‘Coffee output to dip next season - but not by much’, 13 June 2011<br />
<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/news/coffee-output-to-dip-next-season---but-not-by-much--3250.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/news/coffee-output-to-dip-next-season---but-not...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>With price swings of between 17 and 20%, volatility in international coffee prices raises the issue of price transmission from international markets to producers, and what steps ACP producers and governments can take to maximise the earnings potential of coffee exports. In the EU, faced with price volatility, farmers in the cereals sector are adopting various techniques of forward-selling their crops to try to lock in high prices, while leaving flexibility to capitalise on any future price rises. In the cocoa sector in Ghana, the centralised Cocobod also heavily relies on forward selling in order to preserve producer price.</p><p>It is unclear to what extent such an approach is possible elsewhere in the ACP coffee sector, given the auction-based marketing of much of the ACP’s coffee production and the smallholder-based nature of ACP coffee production.</p><p>For arabica coffee, better marketing – for example through regionally based joint promotion of quality-differentiated coffees such as single-origin coffees, GI protected coffees, organic and fair-trade coffees – could offer one means of insulating some ACP suppliers from price volatility. However this may require donor-financed ‘pump-priming’ assistance to get embryonic initiatives off the ground.</p><p>Considerable scope would also appear to exist for pan-ACP exchanges of experience on how to ensure that coffee producers fully benefit from the price premiums payable on quality-differentiated coffees.</p>
		</div>
		
